<p>Our experience in using the quadratic formula on quadratic equations with real coefficients has shown us that complex roots always appear in conjugate pairs. For example, the roots of <m>x^{2} - 2x + 5 = 0</m> are <m>1 + 2i</m> and <m>1 - 2i</m>. In fact, this property extends to all polynomial equations with real coefficients.</p>
<table>
