<p>Radical notation is an alternative way of writing an expression with rational exponents. We define for real number <m>a</m>, the <m>n^{\text{th}}</m> root of <m>a</m> as follows:</p>
<table>
<tabular>
<row>
<cell><alert>Definition 3.18 (</alert><m>n^{\text{th}}</m> <alert>root of</alert> <m>a</m><alert>):</alert> <m>\sqrt[n]{a}</m>= <m>a^{\frac{1}{n}}</m>, where <m>n</m> is a positive integer.</cell>
</row>
</tabular>
</table>
<p>The number <m>\sqrt[n]{a}</m> is also called the principal <m>n^{\text{th}}</m> root of <m>a</m>. If the <m>n^{\text{th}}</m> root of <m>a</m> exists, we have:</p>
